    <section id="glossary">
      <h2>Glossary of key terms</h2>
      <dl class="glossary">
        <dt>SAAR</dt>
        <dd>Seasonally Adjusted Annual Rate — quarterly growth expressed as if that pace persisted for a full year.</dd>

        <dt>PCE / Core PCE</dt>
        <dd>Personal Consumption Expenditures price index; “core” excludes food and energy. It is the Fed’s preferred inflation gauge <a class="ref" href="#ref-3">[R3]</a>.</dd>

        <dt>Fed funds rate (FFR)</dt>
        <dd>The overnight policy rate targeted by the Federal Reserve, quoted as a range (e.g., 4.00–4.25%) <a class="ref" href="#ref-1">[R1]</a>.</dd>

        <dt>10Y UST / 10Y TIPS / Real yield</dt>
        <dd>Market yields on 10‑year U.S. Treasuries; TIPS are inflation‑indexed. “Real yield” ≈ TIPS yield; higher real yields pressure valuation multiples <a class="ref" href="#ref-4">[R4]</a> <a class="ref" href="#ref-5">[R5]</a>.</dd>

        <dt>Breakeven inflation</dt>
        <dd>The difference between nominal and TIPS yields of the same maturity — the market‑implied inflation rate.</dd>

        <dt>OAS (Option‑Adjusted Spread)</dt>
        <dd>Credit spread after adjusting for embedded options; common measure for high‑yield (HY) and investment‑grade (IG) bonds <a class="ref" href="#ref-7">[R7]</a>.</dd>

        <dt>ERP (Equity Risk Premium)</dt>
        <dd>Excess of equity earnings yield over risk‑free yields; a thin ERP implies less cushion if earnings or rates move the wrong way.</dd>

        <dt>Forward P/E</dt>
        <dd>Price divided by next‑twelve‑months earnings per share (consensus). Often used for valuation snapshots <a class="ref" href="#ref-10">[R10]</a>.</dd>

        <dt>Q4/Q4</dt>
        <dd>Growth measured from the fourth quarter of one year to the fourth quarter of the next, a common way to summarize annual momentum.</dd>

        <dt>DXY</dt>
        <dd>The U.S. Dollar Index, a weighted basket of major trading partner currencies.</dd>

        <dt>De‑minimis (Section 321)</dt>
        <dd>A customs rule allowing low‑value imports to enter with minimal duties; its suspension/limitation raises landed costs for some importers <a class="ref" href="#ref-13">[R13]</a>.</dd>

        <dt>Term premium / curve steepening</dt>
        <dd>Extra compensation for holding long‑dated bonds; “steepening” means long rates rise relative to short rates.</dd>

        <dt>BB/B ex‑CCC</dt>
        <dd>Higher‑quality segments within HY (excluding the riskiest CCC‑rated bonds).</dd>
      </dl>
    </section>

